===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|day|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|dæg|dæġ|day|lang=ang|sc=Latinx}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|dagaz||day|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|dʰegʰ-||to burn|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|dei||day|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|dag||day|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Tag||day|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|dag||day|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|dagur||day|lang=is}}. Compare {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|djeg||to burn|lang=sq}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|degti||to burn|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term||tr=dāhas||heat|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}.

Not related to Latin {{term|dies|lang=la}} (from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|dyeu-||to shine|lang=ine-pro}}).

